\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
7.14.14.

\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.37.

\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 is proved.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.39.

\series default
 Evaluate the proof of the following result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Result 
\series default
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 If 3n − 8 is odd, then n is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof 
\series default
Assume that n isodd.Then n = 2k+1 for some integer k.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 3n − 8 = 3 (2k+1) − 8 = 6k + 3 − 8 = 6k − 5 = 2(3k − 3) + 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 3k − 3 is an integer, 3n − 8 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof Eval
\series default
 This proof is incorrect; it proves the converse of the implication rather
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
than the implication itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.41.

\series default
 The following is an attempted proof of a result.
 What is the
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
result and is the attempted proof correct?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof
\series default
 Assume, without loss of generality, that x is even.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then x = 2a for some integer a.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{2}=\left(2a\right)y^{2}=2\left(ay^{2}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(ay^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 is an integer, 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof Eval
\series default
 Judging by the first sentence and the fourth, it would seem that the 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
result being proved here is something along the lines of:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $xy^{2}$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that this is the statement being proven, the give proof is incorrect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It failed to account for the possibility that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is odd (WLOG, making 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 oboslete).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right way to do this would be to present two cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case 1.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Case 2.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
3.43.

\series default
 A direct proof of the statement:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in Z$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $7x-3$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $3x+8$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
is given with the help of a lemma:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $7x-3$
\end_inset

 is even, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is odd.
\end_layout

